President Obama has announced his intent to appoint several individuals to key administration posts, specifically the President's Committee on the Arts and the Humanities. The appointees include Chuck Close, a visual artist known for his innovative portrait paintings; Fred Goldring, co-founder of an entertainment law firm and strategic consultancy; Sheila Johnson, founder and CEO of Salamander Hospitality and co-founder of Black Entertainment Television; Pamela Joyner, founder of Avid Partners and trustee of various arts organizations; Jhumpa Lahiri, a Pulitzer Prize-winning fiction writer; and Ken Solomon, chairman of Ovation TV and Tennis Channel. President Obama emphasized the importance of the arts and humanities in enhancing society and strengthening democracy.